<paper id="1529387115"><title>Answers for disjunctive logic programs</title><year>1991</year><authors><author org="University of Koblenz" id="2716606048">Ulrich Furbach</author></authors><n_citation>3</n_citation><doc_type /><references><reference>1514729613</reference><reference>1520081795</reference><reference>1530765221</reference><reference>1591091340</reference><reference>1605976683</reference><reference>2082367267</reference><reference>2084894656</reference><reference>2148853609</reference></references><venue id="" type="">GWAI '91 15. Fachtagung für Künstliche Intelligenz,</venue><doi>10.1007/978-3-662-02711-0_3</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.60765">Operational semantics</keyword><keyword weight="0.57378">Horn clause</keyword><keyword weight="0.45077">Programming language</keyword><keyword weight="0.43984">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.59475">Disjunctive normal form</keyword><keyword weight="0.65834">Stable model semantics</keyword><keyword weight="0.59031">Predicate functor logic</keyword><keyword weight="0.55972">Logic programming</keyword><keyword weight="0.57495">Dynamic logic (modal logic)</keyword><keyword weight="0.60929">Higher-order logic</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>In this paper indefinite answers for disjunctive logic programs are investigated. A fixpoint semantics which is known from the literature is discussed and a result concerning its correspondence to a minimal model semantics is improved. As an operational semantics V-resolution is proposed and its answer correctness and completeness is proved. Finally the use of the splitting rule for computing answers for disjunctive logic programs is depicted.</abstract></paper>